## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

This code has several constructs that **break or behave differently** in .NET 8. Here's the full analysis and migrated code.

### ⚠️ Critical Pitfalls in the Original Code

| Issue | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `ThreadAbortException` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Wakes blocking calls | Marked `[Obsolete]`, unreliable |
| `ManualResetEvent` + manual `lock` | Works but has a **race condition**: multiple rapid `Enqueue` calls can be lost because `Reset()` fires before the queue is fully drained | Same bug, but modern alternatives exist |
| No cancellation support | Common pattern at the time | `CancellationToken` is the standard now |

### Race Condition in the Original

```
Thread A: Enqueue("a")  →  Set()
Thread A: Enqueue("b")  →  Set()    // signal already set — no-op
Thread B: WaitOne() returns
Thread B: Reset()                    // clears signal
Thread B: Dequeue() → "a"
Thread B: WaitOne() → BLOCKS        // "b" is stuck in queue forever
```

---

### ✅ Migrated Code (.NET 8)

The idiomatic replacement uses `Channel<T>` — a high-performance, thread-safe, async-native producer/consumer primitive that eliminates the manual synchronization entirely:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Graceful shutdown — expected when Stop is called
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete();   // signal no more items

        // Give the worker time to drain, then force-cancel
        using var timeoutCts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        try
        {
            await _workerTask.WaitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
        }
        catch (TimeoutException)
        {
            await _cts.CancelAsync();  // force cancel — replaces Thread.Abort()
            await _workerTask;         // wait for clean exit
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // your processing logic
    }
}
```

### Key Migration Decisions

| Old Pattern | New Pattern | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread` + `ManualResetEvent` | `Task.Run` + `Channel<T>` | No manual sync needed; no lost-signal race condition |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` | Only supported shutdown mechanism in .NET 8 |
| `lock` + `Queue<T>` | `Channel<T>` | Thread-safe by design, back-pressure support built in |
| `thread.Join(5000)` | `WaitAsync` + timeout | Non-blocking, composable with async code |
| `IDisposable` (implicit) | `IAsyncDisposable` | Ensures cleanup in DI / `await using` scenarios |

### If `Handle()` is async

Replace the loop body:

```csharp
await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
{
    await HandleAsync(item, ct);
}
```

### If you need bounded back-pressure

```csharp
// Blocks producers when 100 items are buffered
Channel.CreateBounded<string>(new BoundedChannelOptions(100)
{
    FullMode = BoundedChannelFullMode.Wait
});
```

The `Channel<T>` approach eliminates the entire class of threading bugs present in the original while being faster (lock-free internally) and idiomatic for .NET 8.
